  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Differentiated thyroid cancer: iodine's best friend, cancer's worst enemy.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B and C. Radioactive iodine (RAI) is an effective treatment for metastatic lung disease in patients with papillary and follicular thyroid carcinomas because these are differentiated thyroid cancers that retain the ability to trap iodine.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDifferentiated thyroid carcinomas, specifically papillary and follicular types, retain the expression of the sodium-iodide symporter (NIS) protein. This protein allows the cancer cells to actively transport iodine from the bloodstream into the cell, mimicking normal thyroid function. Radioactive iodine (131I) exploits this mechanism, delivering targeted radiation to these iodine-avid cells, including distant metastases. For optimal therapeutic effect, normal thyroid tissue must be absent (typically achieved via total thyroidectomy) to eliminate competition for iodine uptake. While most papillary carcinomas are iodine-avid, some variants (e.g., tall cell, insular) may have reduced uptake. Follicular carcinomas, however, almost universally retain significant iodine uptake capabilities.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Hürthle cell carcinoma): (Incorrect): Although a variant of follicular carcinoma, Hürthle cell carcinoma often exhibits poor or absent iodine uptake, rendering radioactive iodine therapy largely ineffective.\nOption D (Medullary carcinoma): (Incorrect): Medullary thyroid carcinoma originates from parafollicular C-cells, which are neuroendocrine cells and do not produce thyroid hormone or express the sodium-iodide symporter, thus they do not take up iodine.\nOption E (Anaplastic carcinoma): (Incorrect): Anaplastic thyroid carcinoma is a highly aggressive and undifferentiated cancer that has lost all functional characteristics of normal thyroid cells, including the ability to take up iodine.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Papillary Carcinoma | Follicular Carcinoma | Medullary Carcinoma | Anaplastic Carcinoma |\n| :------------------ | :------------------ | :------------------- | :------------------ | :------------------- |\n| Cell Origin | Follicular cells | Follicular cells | Parafollicular C-cells | Follicular cells (dedifferentiated) |\n| Differentiation | Well-differentiated | Well-differentiated | Neuroendocrine | Undifferentiated |\n| RAI Uptake | Good (most) | Excellent (most) | None | None |\n| Prognosis | Excellent | Good | Variable | Very Poor |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Only differentiated thyroid cancers take up radioactive iodine.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPost-RAI whole-body scans (WBS) would show uptake in residual thyroid bed tissue and metastatic lesions (e.g., lung, bone) in patients with papillary or follicular carcinoma. Intraoperatively, these cancers might appear as solid, firm nodules.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (2015/2023) recommend RAI for selected patients with differentiated thyroid cancer and metastatic disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hürthle cell carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Papillary carcinoma | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Follicular carcinoma | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Medullary carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Anaplastic carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C) Radioactive iodine is used only in patients who have differentiated thyroid carcinomas. It is of no ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 385388882-1.pdf**\n",
