  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Papillary thyroid cancer: common, complex, and a pediatric challenge.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nAll statements regarding papillary thyroid carcinoma are true, reflecting its high prevalence, specific management for minimal disease, common multicentricity, and age-dependent lymph node involvement. This question tests comprehensive knowledge of PTC epidemiology, pathology, and initial management principles.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPapillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) is the most common thyroid malignancy, accounting for 70-80% of new cases in the United States. Its management is nuanced; for minimal disease (0.5-1 cm), a total ipsilateral lobectomy and isthmus resection are considered adequate therapy. A key pathological feature is its high rate of multicentricity, with microscopic foci found in 70-80% of cases upon serial sectioning. Furthermore, age is a significant prognostic factor for lymph node involvement, with nearly all patients under 15 years old presenting with metastatic disease in local lymph nodes, though this doesn't always impact long-term survival for intrathyroidal primaries.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Correct): Seventy to 80% of new thyroid carcinoma cases in the US are papillary type, confirming its high prevalence.\nOption B (Correct): For minimal thyroid carcinoma (0.5-1 cm), total ipsilateral lobectomy and isthmus resection are satisfactory, demonstrating appropriate surgical management for small, contained lesions.\nOption C (Correct): Microscopic evidence of multicentric disease is found in 70% to 80% of cases upon serial sectioning, highlighting a common pathological characteristic.\nOption D (Correct): Nearly all patients less than 15 years of age have metastatic disease in local lymph nodes, emphasizing the age-dependent aggressive behavior in pediatric populations.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Description | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Prevalence** | 70-80% of new thyroid carcinoma cases in the US | Most common thyroid cancer |\n| **Minimal PTC** | <1 cm, no clinical lymph node mets | Lobectomy + isthmus for 0.5-1 cm |\n| **Multicentricity** | Microscopic foci in 70-80% of cases | Common pathological finding, influences extent of surgery |\n| **Lymph Node Mets (<15 yrs)** | Nearly all patients have local lymph node involvement | Age is a strong predictor of nodal disease |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Papillary thyroid cancer is common, often multifocal, and aggressive in the young.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, PTC often appears as a hypoechoic nodule with microcalcifications, irregular margins, and increased vascularity. Intraoperatively, multicentricity might be appreciated as additional small nodules within the gland, and suspicious lymph nodes in the central or lateral neck compartments would prompt dissection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines 2015: These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the management of thyroid nodules and differentiated thyroid cancer, including surgical extent based on tumor size, multifocality, and patient age.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Seventy to 80% of new cases of thyroid carcinoma in the United States are o | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Total ipsilateral lobectomy and isthmus resection are adequate therapy for  | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Microscopic evidence of multicentric disease is present in 70% to 80% of ca | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Nearly all patients less than 15 years of age have metastatic disease in lo | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C, D) Seventy to 80% of the 11,000 new patients with thyroid carcinoma diagnosed annually in the United St** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 385388882-1.pdf**\n",
