  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Thyroid hormones: T4 is the factory, T3 is the worker, free is the key!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies key aspects of thyroid hormone synthesis, metabolism, and cellular action. Options A, B, and C are true statements reflecting fundamental thyroid physiology, while option D contains an inaccuracy regarding binding protein proportions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe thyroid gland is the sole endogenous source of T4, while the majority of T3 is produced by peripheral deiodination of T4 in tissues like the liver and kidney, with only about 20% secreted directly by the thyroid. Once released, thyroid hormones are largely bound to plasma proteins, primarily thyroid-binding globulin (TBG), which ensures solubility and systemic distribution, with only the free forms being metabolically active. At the cellular level, excess thyroid hormone increases the number of ATP-dependent sodium pumps, thereby elevating resting energy expenditure and oxygen consumption, and also facilitates glucose and amino acid transport.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): The majority of thyroid hormone in circulating plasma is bound to thyroid-binding globulin (TBG, 85%), not albumin (10%). While binding does limit the availability of the metabolically active free form, the primary binding protein is TBG.\nOption A (Correct): Normally about 20% of T3 is secreted directly from the thyroid gland.\nOption B (Correct): The thyroid gland is the only endogenous source of T4.\nOption C (Correct): Excess thyroid hormone results in an increase in the number of ATP-dependent sodium pumps on the cell membrane.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | T4 (Thyroxine) | T3 (Triiodothyronine) |\n| :------ | :------------- | :-------------------- |\n| Primary Source | Thyroid gland (100% endogenous) | Peripheral conversion of T4 (80%) |\n| Direct Thyroid Secretion | 100% | ~20% |\n| Potency | Less potent | More potent |\n| Major Plasma Binder | TBG (85%) | TBG (85%) |\n| Active Form | Free T4 | Free T3 |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: T4 is thyroid-made, T3 is mostly T4-converted; free forms are active.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, the thyroid gland's size, echotexture, and vascularity (e.g., increased flow in Graves' disease) can reflect its physiological state. Intraoperatively, a hyperactive gland may appear enlarged and hypervascular.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Hyperthyroidism and Other Causes of Thyrotoxicosis (2016) recommend specific diagnostic criteria and treatment strategies based on thyroid hormone physiology.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Normally about 20% of T3 is secreted directly from the thyroid gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The thyroid gland is the only endogenous source of T4 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Excess thyroid hormone results in an increase in the number of ATP-dependen | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | The majority of thyroid hormone in circulating plasma is bound to albumin,  | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, b, c) The thyroid is the only endogenous source of T4, whereas most T3 is produced by the peripheral conve** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 385388882-1.pdf**\n",
