  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, CT the adrenal out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Computed Tomography (CT) because it is the most commonly used and reliable initial imaging technique for detecting adrenal abnormalities. While other modalities have specific uses, CT offers the best balance of accessibility, sensitivity, and non-invasiveness for general adrenal assessment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCT reliably detects adrenal tumors greater than 1 cm in diameter, with sensitivity reaching 100% for larger lesions (3-4 cm). It is a non-invasive procedure that serves as the primary screening tool when adrenal abnormalities are suspected. Although CT is non-specific regarding tumor function or benign/malignant nature, its ability to accurately localize and size lesions makes it the optimal first-line imaging choice.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Ultrasound) (Incorrect): Its value is limited by the adrenal gland's relative inaccessibility and its poor detection of small lesions.\nOption C (Arteriography) (Incorrect): This is an invasive procedure with inherent risks, has become less popular, and is specifically dangerous in patients with pheochromocytomas.\nOption D (Scintigraphy with 131I-6 b-iodomethyl-19-norcholesterol (NP-59)) (Incorrect): This technique is specific for imaging adrenocortical lesions and functioning tumors, not a general screening tool for all adrenal abnormalities.\nOption E (Scintigraphy with 131I-methaiodobenzylguanidine (MIBG)) (Incorrect): This technique is specific for localizing pheochromocytomas by detecting norepinephrine accumulation, not a general imaging modality for all adrenal pathologies.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Primary Use/Strength | Limitations/Specificity |\n|---|---|---|\n| **CT** | Initial detection of adrenal lesions, sizing | Non-specific (cannot distinguish benign/malignant, functioning/non-functioning) |\n| **MRI** | Characterization of lesions, distinguishing types (e.g., adenoma vs. pheochromocytoma), anatomic relationships | More expensive, requires patient cooperation, less available than CT |\n| **Ultrasound** | Least expensive | Limited by adrenal inaccessibility, poor detection of small lesions |\n| **NP-59 Scintigraphy** | Imaging adrenocortical lesions, distinguishing hyperplasia from adenomas/carcinomas | Specific for cortical lesions, not general screening |\n| **MIBG Scintigraphy** | Localizing pheochromocytomas (especially multiple, extra-adrenal, recurrent) | Specific for pheochromocytomas, not general screening |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: CT is the workhorse for initial adrenal lesion detection.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a CT scan, adrenal lesions appear as distinct masses or nodules in the suprarenal region. Their size, density (e.g., low attenuation for adenomas), and enhancement patterns after contrast administration provide crucial information for initial characterization.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society's Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Adrenal Incidentalomas (2016) recommends CT as the initial imaging modality for characterizing adrenal incidentalomas, with MRI as an alternative, especially for further characterization.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ultrasound | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Computed tomography (CT) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Arteriography | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Scintigraphy with 131I-6 b-iodomethyl-19-norcholesterol (NP-59) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Scintigraphy with 131I-methaiodobenzylguanidine (MIBG) | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: b) Although ultrasonography is the least expensive of the imaging procedures, its value is limited by t** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 385388882-1.pdf**\n",
