  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't rush to cut a quiet adrenal lump!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C because an asymptomatic, nonfunctional adrenal nodule of 2 cm is typically managed conservatively with surveillance due to its low risk of malignancy and non-functional status. Immediate surgical intervention is reserved for larger or functionally active lesions. This approach prioritizes patient safety and avoids unnecessary invasive procedures.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdrenal incidentalomas are common findings, and their management hinges on size and functional status. For non-functional lesions, size is the primary determinant for intervention. Nodules less than 4 cm, especially those under 3 cm, are generally considered low risk for malignancy and are managed with active surveillance, including repeat imaging and hormonal re-evaluation. The initial follow-up CT scan in 1 to 3 months helps assess for rapid growth, which would be a concerning sign, followed by less frequent surveillance if stable.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Extraperitoneal right adrenalectomy is an appropriate surgical approach but is not indicated for a 2 cm non-functional adrenal nodule. Surgery is typically reserved for lesions >4-6 cm, those with suspicious imaging features, or functional activity.\nOption B (Incorrect): Suppression with prednisone is not a treatment for an adrenal nodule. Prednisone is a corticosteroid and would suppress endogenous adrenal function, which is not the goal here, especially for a non-functional lesion.\nOption D (Incorrect): Excisional biopsy via laparoscopic approach is an unnecessary and potentially harmful intervention for a small, non-functional adrenal nodule. Biopsy of adrenal lesions is generally discouraged due to risks of hemorrhage, tumor seeding (if malignant), and often inconclusive results, especially for small lesions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Non-functional Adrenal Nodule < 4 cm | Non-functional Adrenal Nodule > 6 cm | Functional Adrenal Nodule (any size) |\n| :-------------------------------- | :----------------------------------- | :----------------------------------- | :----------------------------------- |\n| **Management** | Active surveillance (repeat imaging/hormonal) | Surgical resection | Surgical resection |\n| **Malignancy Risk** | Low | Higher | Variable, but often removed due to hormonal effects |\n| **Follow-up** | CT scan at 6-12 months, then annually | N/A (surgery) | N/A (surgery) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Small, non-functional adrenal incidentalomas get surveillance, not surgery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a 2 cm solid adrenal nodule would appear as a well-defined, rounded or oval mass in the adrenal gland. Its density (Hounsfield units) and washout characteristics would be assessed to help differentiate benign adenomas from other lesions, with lower Hounsfield units (<10 HU) and rapid washout suggesting benignity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Clinical Endocrinologists (AACE) and American Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Medical Guidelines for the Management of Adrenal Incidentalomas (2023). These guidelines recommend surveillance for non-functional lesions <4 cm.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Extraperitoneal right adrenalectomy through either a flank of posterior app | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Suppression with 5 mg prednisone PO qod | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Followup CT scan in 1 to 3 months | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Excisional biopsy via laparaoscopic approach | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: c) Indication for operation in the patient with a unilateral functioning adrenal tumor is clear. In the** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 385388882-1.pdf**\n",
