  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Alpha-blockade before surgery: No pheo-no-go!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis patient presents with a large adrenal mass and significantly elevated 24-hour urine norepinephrine, indicative of a pheochromocytoma. The initial and critical step in preoperative preparation for pheochromocytoma is alpha-adrenergic blockade to prevent a life-threatening hypertensive crisis during surgery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe elevated norepinephrine levels confirm the diagnosis of pheochromocytoma, a catecholamine-secreting tumor. Preoperative management mandates alpha-adrenergic blockade, typically with phenoxybenzamine, to control blood pressure and prevent catecholamine-induced vasoconstriction and hypertensive crises during tumor manipulation. This blockade ensures vasodilation, allowing for volume expansion and preventing severe hypotension post-tumor removal. Beta-blockers like labetalol should only be added *after* adequate alpha-blockade to avoid unopposed alpha-stimulation, which can worsen hypertension.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Treatment with spironolactone) (Incorrect): Spironolactone is an aldosterone antagonist used in the management of primary hyperaldosteronism, not pheochromocytoma. The patient's 18-hydroxycorticosterone level is normal, ruling out hyperaldosteronism.\nOption B (Intravenous potassium-loading to prevent intraoperative hypokalemia) (Incorrect): Potassium supplementation is indicated for hypokalemia, which is a common feature of primary hyperaldosteronism, not pheochromocytoma. This patient's presentation does not suggest hyperaldosteronism.\nOption D (Treatment with labetalol) (Incorrect): Labetalol is a combined alpha and beta-blocker. While it has alpha-blocking properties, using a beta-blocker (even a combined one) *before* adequate pure alpha-blockade in pheochromocytoma can lead to unopposed alpha-adrenergic vasoconstriction, potentially exacerbating hypertension and causing pulmonary edema.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Diagnostic Marker | Initial Preoperative Treatment |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pheochromocytoma | Elevated urine/plasma metanephrines/catecholamines | Alpha-blockade (e.g., Phenoxybenzamine) |\n| Primary Hyperaldosteronism | Elevated plasma aldosterone/renin ratio, high 18-hydroxycorticosterone | Spironolactone, potassium replacement |\n| Cushing's Syndrome | Elevated 24-hour urine free cortisol, dexamethasone suppression test | Metyrapone, ketoconazole (medical adrenalectomy) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Alpha-blockade FIRST for pheochromocytoma, always.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, a pheochromocytoma typically appears as a well-circumscribed, often heterogeneous adrenal mass, frequently with high signal intensity on T2-weighted MRI. Intraoperatively, these tumors can be highly vascular and may appear reddish-brown, often encapsulated, and manipulation can trigger significant hemodynamic instability.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for Pheochromocytoma and Paraganglioma (2014) recommends preoperative alpha-adrenergic blockade for 7-14 days to normalize blood pressure and expand intravascular volume.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Treatment with spironolactone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Intravenous potassium-loading to prevent intraoperative hypokalemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Treatment with phenoxybenzamine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Treatment with labetalol | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: c) This patient has a pheochromocytoma. The most efficient and sensitive means of screening for pheochr** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 385388882-1.pdf**\n",
