  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pituitary problems: high prolactin, poor vision, and no period.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answers, serum prolactin levels and MRI of the brain, are appropriate diagnostic tests for a 30-year-old woman presenting with amenorrhea, headache, and bitemporal hemianopsia. This constellation of symptoms strongly suggests a pituitary lesion, which can cause both mass effect and hormonal dysfunction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPituitary lesions, particularly prolactinomas, commonly present with endocrine symptoms like amenorrhea due to hypersecretion of hormones. The mass effect of an enlarging pituitary tumor often compresses the optic chiasm, leading to the classic bitemporal hemianopsia. MRI is the gold standard for imaging pituitary adenomas, capable of detecting small lesions and delineating their extent, while serum prolactin levels directly assess hormonal activity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption a (Cerebral angiography) (Incorrect): This is reserved for suspicion of an aneurysm or significant internal carotid artery compression, not for initial diagnosis of a pituitary mass.\nOption d (Abdominal and pelvic CT scan) (Incorrect): This scan is irrelevant for symptoms pointing to a central nervous system and pituitary etiology, such as headache, visual field defects, and amenorrhea.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Test | Indication for Pituitary Lesion | Key Finding/Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| Serum Prolactin Levels | Amenorrhea, galactorrhea, infertility | Detects prolactin-secreting adenomas (prolactinomas) |\n| MRI of the Brain | Suspected pituitary mass effect or endocrine dysfunction | Gold standard for visualizing tumor size, location, and extension |\n| CT Scan of the Brain | Alternative if MRI is contraindicated or unavailable | Can identify larger lesions but less detailed than MRI |\n| Cerebral Angiography | Suspected aneurysm or significant ICA compression | Evaluates vascular structures, not primary tumor imaging |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Amenorrhea + bitemporal hemianopsia = think pituitary, image with MRI, check prolactin.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, one would typically see an intrasellar mass, potentially with suprasellar extension compressing the optic chiasm, and possibly lateral extension into the cavernous sinuses. Gadolinium enhancement helps delineate the tumor from surrounding structures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline: Diagnosis and Management of Prolactinomas (2011, updated 2023) recommends serum prolactin measurement and MRI of the pituitary for suspected prolactinomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | Cerebral angiography | ❌ Incorrect |\n| b | Serum prolactin levels | ✅ Correct |\n| c | Magnetic resonance imaging of the brain | ✅ Correct |\n| d | Abdominal and pelvic CT scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: b, c) Patients with pituitary lesions present symptoms and signs related to a mass effect on the pituitary** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 385388882-1.pdf**\n",
